Movie: Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again

Review: So it's very clear now that Chazelle wrote LA La Land before he knew what the dream was *really* all about, and then wrote this about the disillusionment of that dream. Very fascinating stuff and the ending was really effective but whenever Manny wasn't the focus I was less invested. Didn't buy Brad Pitt one bit the other performances ran solid to great.

I dissociated through this in theaters because the visual style, most of the jokes, and entire subplots just flew right over my head and as a result I spent the past 15 years ago thinking this movie was mid and forgettable but honestly this was incredibly ahead of its time and is one of the more fully realized movies I have ever seen. Every moment a delight. Holy shit. This is joining the rotation.

Y'all really had me thinking we were getting another Love and Thunder but this was a blast?? Certainly not a movie I'd watch if I wanted to watch something that had anything resembling a theme or character arc, but sometimes you're just really stoned and all you need is some full throttle Silver Age camp. This movie delivered on that front. Arguably the best live action Fantastic Four movie ever made.

Movie: Puss in Boots: The Last Wish
Review: I've seen this like eight more times and I need to up my ranking. This may be even better than Paddington 2. This is a truly excellent endlessly rewatchable and quotable movie. Instant classic.

Movie: Puss in Boots: The Last Wish
Review: I've seen this like eight more times and I need to up my ranking. This may be even better than Paddington 2. This is a truly excellent endlessly rewatchable and quotable movie. Instant classic.
Pretty much the only thing I thought during this movie was "yup, that's Lydia Tar."
DreamWorks has seriously upped their standards.
Enjoyed it thoroughly while watching it but admittedly not left knowing how I really felt about this one. Gonna need to give it a few more watches to really know. Looks gorgeous for sure.

So many plot threads are left dangling that I had to google if there was a director's cut of this movie or not because there was no way that many scenes were left without context on purpose. Turns out there is one! I don't feel particularly inclined to watch it.
Jupiter and Beyond the Infinite continues to be the best part of this movie.

Movie: The Good, the Bad and the Ugly

Review: Maybe I'd just never watched this stoned before but I'd severely underrated this movie in the past. Disney has never made anything quite on this level ever since.
Yes to Revolting Children, no to fat suits. When I Grow Up continues to make me cry.
